{
  "texts": [
    "Far from an arbitrary add-on to the extended cognition project, her account is motivated by a similarly sceptical attitude to that taken by HEC's supporters toward a conception of the mind and its environment as constitutively distinct spheres, separated by what Hurley (1998) memorably describes as the \"magic membrane\" of the agent's extra-cranial body (recall also Lavin's \"metaphysical containment wall\").",
    "Instead, Anscombe offers a vision of human rationality (and so cognitive agency) as embedded in and expressed by the material context that people inhabit and construct together.",
    "While, of course, defending HEC was not part of Anscombe's philosophical agenda, this anti-Cartesian theme in her work on mind and action overlaps with some central motivations for later embodied and extended views.",
    "In light of this, recent commentary has noted important points of contact between claims made in the contemporary Anscombean action theoretic literature and those made by in the broad 'embodied cognition' movement that defenders of HEC also participate in (see, e.g., Kalis, 2019; Segundo-Ortin & Kalis, 2022; Britten-Neish, 2022, 2024).",
    "This gives us reason to think that an exploration of her account in light of the action theoretic argument sketched above (in §3.3) will be fruitful."
  ]
}